  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "How Much Protein Per Day After 40? (Simple Answer + Real Example)",
    "description": "Most men over 40 are eating about half the protein they actually need. Here's the real number, what it looks like in practice, and why 90 grams still isn't enough.",
    "url": "https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-per-day-after-40/",
    "author": {
      "@type": "Person",
      "name": "Robert",
      "description": "Founder of SnapProtein, fitness enthusiast, age 64"
    },
    "publisher": {
      "@type": "Organization",
      "name": "SnapProtein",
      "url": "https://snapprotein.com"
    }
  }
  </script>

  <script type="application/ld+json">
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much protein per day do men over 40 need?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Most men over 40 need at least 0.5–0.6 grams of protein per pound of bodyweight per day to protect muscle mass — and closer to 0.7–0.8 grams per pound if they want to stay strong and active. For a 180-pound man, that's roughly 90–145 grams per day. Most men are currently getting less than half that."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is 90 grams of protein a day enough after 40?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For most men over 40, 90 grams per day is a floor — not a finish line. While it's significantly better than the typical intake of 50–60 grams, research suggests that men over 40 benefit from 120–160 grams per day to meaningfully support muscle preservation and offset anabolic resistance. 90 grams sounds like a lot until you see what the actual target is."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Why do men over 40 need more protein than younger men?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "After 40, muscle becomes less responsive to protein — a process called anabolic resistance. The same protein dose that triggered muscle protein synthesis at 28 produces a weaker signal at 48. To compensate, older men need both a higher daily total and larger per-meal doses (30+ grams) to reliably stimulate muscle building."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What does 120 grams of protein per day actually look like?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "120 grams of protein per day across four meals looks like: breakfast with Greek yogurt and eggs (30g), a tuna or chicken lunch (35g), an afternoon cottage cheese snack (25g), and a protein-focused dinner like salmon or chicken breast (35g). It's achievable with real food — no shakes required, though they help fill gaps."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I know if I'm getting enough protein?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Most men don't know — and that's exactly the problem. Tracking your protein for even 5–7 days reveals the gap clearly. Most men discover they're running 40–60 grams short of their daily target. A simple protein tracker that shows your daily number without requiring calorie counting is the most practical tool for this."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
